BUILDING AND INSTALLING XCONQ

Xconq builds with CMake (3.20 or newer) and a C++ compiler such as GCC.

1. Provide the required supporting software.

One interface is available:

  - SDL (sdlconq): needs the SDL 1.2 API; on modern systems this is
    provided by sdl12-compat (e.g. libsdl1.2-compat-dev on Debian/Ubuntu,
    sdl12-compat-devel on Fedora).

(The Tcl/Tk graphical interface and the legacy Xt/Xaw interface were
removed in 7/2026, and the curses interface was removed in 7/2026 -- see
MODERNIZATION-PLAN.md's Step 2 note.)

On Debian/Ubuntu, everything at once:

    sudo apt install cmake g++ libsdl1.2-compat-dev libxmu-dev

On Fedora:

    sudo dnf install cmake gcc-c++ sdl12-compat-devel libXmu-devel

Each interface is built only if its dependencies are found; a missing
dependency produces a warning and that interface is skipped.  The
kernel and the headless test driver (skelconq) always build.

2. Configure and build:

    cmake -B build
    cmake --build build -j

Useful configuration options (pass as -D<option>=<value> to cmake):

    XCONQ_UI_SDL=ON/OFF      Build the SDL interface, sdlconq (default ON)
    CMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX     Installation prefix (default /usr/local)
    XCONQ_SCORES_DIR         Directory for score files at run time, for
                             shared installs (default: empty, meaning
                             per-user scores under $XDG_DATA_HOME/xconq)
    CMAKE_BUILD_TYPE         e.g. Release, Debug, RelWithDebInfo

3. If you want to test things out before installing, run a UI binary
from the build tree with the games library from this distribution:

    ./build/sdl/sdlconq -L lib

4. Run the test suite (uses the headless skelconq driver):

    ctest --test-dir build

Some tests play through long games; skip them with
"ctest --test-dir build --label-exclude long".

5. To install, run:

    cmake --install build

The default installation puts executables into /usr/local/bin and the
game modules and support files into /usr/local/share/xconq.  Use
-DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=<dir> at configure time (or --prefix at install
time) to install elsewhere.

6. The man pages just tell how to start up the programs; the full
Xconq manual has complete details on everything.  A lot of behavior
can be figured out by experimentation and by using the extensive
online help; you can always get to it by typing '?'.

All of the manuals are written in ``Texinfo''.  If makeinfo is
installed, build the info files with:

    cmake --build build --target info

7. If installed in a public place on a multi-user system, announce
availability.  The library file "news.txt" provides a convenient place
to put in any notes about changes, new games/scenarios, and so forth.

Congratulations!  You're ready to go forth and conquer!
